
--- stderr ---
Cannot analyze '.': 'algebraic-variety-cross-section' is not a valid Python module name.

Technical reason:
  pydeps works by generating a synthetic 'dummy' module
  (e.g. _dummy_<target>.py) that contains real Python
  'import <modname>' statements for every submodule of
  the target, then runs Python's modulefinder on that
  dummy to trace the import graph. The 'import' keyword
  is part of Python's grammar and only accepts dotted
  identifiers -- letters, digits, and underscores, and
  not starting with a digit. A name like 'algebraic-variety-cross-section' cannot
  appear on the right-hand side of an import statement,
  so modulefinder has nothing to trace and pydeps
  produces an empty graph.

Fix:
  Rename the offending file or directory so that every
  path component is a valid Python identifier (e.g.
  replace '-' with '_'). If the file must keep its
  on-disk name, point pydeps at a package whose name
  is importable instead.
